metadata.name: Lotka-Volterra Attractor
metadata.description:
The strange attractor appears in the Lotka-Volterra model, which is often used to
describe the dynamics of ecological systems in which several species interact:
predator-prey, host-parasite, competition, and other interspecies interactions.
Interspecies association equations have been proposed as models by Lotka and
Volterra in other publications.
The American mathematician, physical chemist, statistician and demographer Alfred
James Lotka studied the process of generational change, the economic and
demographic aspects of health care, and the evolution of life expectancy.
Vito Volterra is an Italian mathematician and physicist. After World War I, his interest
shifted to the application of mathematical ideas to biology. The most famous result of
this workis the development of the Lotka-Volterra model.
The most common application of the model in economics is the description of
coincidences in stock markets, technological competition, marketing, and trade
relations.
